\subsubsection{Geometry of the Critical Manifold}
\paragraph{Elliptic Paraboloid Interpretation.}
For a fixed surface skin temperature $T_s$, the active branch can be mapped explicitly as a graph over the horizontal velocity coordinates:
\begin{equation}
e=l_0\left[\eta\gamma(U^2+V^2)-K\,G(T_s)\right]-\delta.
\end{equation}
The Hessian eigenvalues determine the local principal curvatures of the graph. Due to the rotational symmetry of the mechanical production term, these eigenvalues are degenerate ($\lambda_1 = \lambda_2 = 2\eta\gamma$), forming perfectly circular cross-sections centered about the non-turbulent geostrophic core.

\subsubsection{Physical and Dynamical Interpretation}
In low-roughness environments such as CASES99, strong surface cooling ($T_s \ll T_a$) amplifies $G(T_s)$, shifts the active branch downward in $e$, and expands the critical radius in the $(U,V)$ plane required to sustain turbulence. As active turbulence vanishes, the frictional drag terms in Equations~\eqref{eq:slow_u} and \eqref{eq:slow_v} are suppressed:
\begin{equation}
\gamma\sqrt{e+\delta}\to\gamma\sqrt{\delta}\approx0,
\end{equation}
which detaches the slow momentum vector from steady frictional balance and permits expansive clockwise Blackadar inertial circuits around $(U_g,V_g)$ at frequency $f$. The model therefore derives inertial oscillations from the governing equations rather than prescribing them phenomenologically.

\subsubsection{Numerical and Statistical Implications}
The local quadratic-fit RMSE is interpreted as a geometric proxy for phase-space exploration. High-roughness regimes such as FLOSS increase drag damping, confining trajectories to a narrower neighborhood and reducing fit error, while lower-roughness regimes such as CASES99 permit broader excursions across nonlinear manifold sectors and therefore larger geometric approximation error.

\paragraph{\texorpdfstring{$C^\infty$}{C-infinity} Regularization.}
To prevent gradient discontinuities near the active-to-laminar transition, the reduced diagnostic branch can be regularized via a smooth hyperbolic embedding parameterized by $0<\xi\ll1$:
\begin{equation}
e^*_{\xi}=\frac{1}{2}\left(e^*+\sqrt{(e^*)^2+\xi^2}\right).
\end{equation}
This is a standard $C^\infty$ approximation to the positive-part map and ensures that the reduced closures for momentum and heat exchange, $K_{m,h}\propto\sqrt{e^*_{\xi}+\delta}$, remain strictly smooth over the diagnostic domain. In the full ODE, the implemented solver adds a separate smooth floor gate to the fast tendency as $e\to-\delta$, so the state remains numerically forward-invariant while still transitioning smoothly between active shear-driven mixing and the residual laminar floor.
